\b\fs22 Examples of running PTXprint from the command-line (in Windows):\b0\fs20\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -c Diglot XYZ\cf0\par
will OPEN PTXprint with XYZ project active and the saved configuration called "Diglot" (but won't print anything)\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -c NTandPsalms -P XYZ\cf0\par
will directly create a PDF from the XYZ project using the saved configuration called "NTandPsalms" (no GUI will appear)\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -b ROM -c SideXrefs -P XYZ\cf0\par
will directly create a PDF of ROMANS from the XYZ project using the saved configuration called "SideXrefs" (no GUI will appear)\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -b "MAT MRK LUK JHN ACT GLO" -P XYZ\cf0\par
will directly create a PDF of 4 gospels, Acts and Glossary from the XYZ project using the Default configuration (no GUI will appear)\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -p C:\\Data\\VariousUSFMprojects\cf0\par
with -p (lowercase) and a folder name will run PTXprint pointing to that folder instead of the usual Paratext folder. Note that\par
it expects one or more subfolders which contain the actual USFM files. The names of any subfolders containing valid .SFM files\par
will appear in the Project drop-down menu once PTXprint has opened.\par
\par
\cf1 "C:\\Program Files\\PTXprint\\PTXprint.exe" -d "C:\\Temp"\cf0\par
runs PTXprint, and output PDF files will be created in C:\\Temp folder instead of C:\\My Paratext 9 Projects\\<XYZ>\\local\\ptxprint\par
